Stand by, VTR.

00:18.385 --> 00:20.376
-- Georgia Dome's hot.
-- You're hot, Atlanta.

00:20.453 --> 00:23.718
Somebody, Arrowhead, then back to
Mile High -- is that how it goes?

00:23.790 --> 00:25.280
We're live here
in 60 seconds.

00:25.358 --> 00:26.951
Somebody? Anybody?

00:27.027 --> 00:27.994
<i>What do you need?</i>

00:28.061 --> 00:29.756
-- Does Arrowhead -- --
Arrowhead bounces to Mile High.

00:29.829 --> 00:31.024
Thank you.

00:31.097 --> 00:32.360
Why'd you change that?

00:32.432 --> 00:35.402
Just to mess with your head.
Get me Judy at Oakland-Alameda.

00:35.468 --> 00:38.165
When you get right down to it,
what I'm saying is this, Case --

00:38.238 --> 00:40.332
I think you should start getting
out of your house.

00:40.407 --> 00:43.308
-- Dan, we're going to Arrowhead
first, then Denver. -- Got it.

00:43.376 --> 00:44.810
Just out of your house.

00:44.878 --> 00:46.039
I am out of my house.

00:46.112 --> 00:48.137
I've been out of my house
for six months.

00:48.214 --> 00:49.545
I don't live at my house.

00:49.616 --> 00:50.879
<i>Man:
30 seconds to tape.</i>

00:50.950 --> 00:53.317
We're coming to the studio
in 90 seconds.

00:53.386 --> 00:54.444
Good evening.

00:54.521 --> 00:56.683
-- Isaac Jaffee's in the
house, Natalie. -- Yo.

00:56.756 --> 00:58.053
We can make a feed on 43.

00:58.124 --> 01:00.456
Just make sure the guys have the change.
[Snaps fingers]

01:00.527 --> 01:03.827
[Shouting] Casey, did you get the
change on Arrowhead and Denver?!

01:03.897 --> 01:06.229
Natalie, if you shout
into a microphone

01:06.299 --> 01:08.199
when I'm wearing an earpiece,
it poses the question

01:08.268 --> 01:10.396
"ls there a decibel level at
which the human head will just,

01:10.470 --> 01:11.665
you know, explode?"

01:11.738 --> 01:13.638
Is he in a better mood
than he was this morning,

01:13.706 --> 01:15.970
or is this gonna be
another crappy show?

01:16.042 --> 01:18.807
Hey, Casey, lsaao wants to know
if you're in a better mood --

01:18.878 --> 01:19.811
Shut up.

01:19.879 --> 01:21.313
Pretty crappy, yeah.

01:21.381 --> 01:23.315
-- Roll tape.
-- Good show, everybody.

01:23.383 --> 01:25.442
<i>Tonight on "Sports Night,"
we'll show you what comes up...</i>

01:25.518 --> 01:27.816
Dan, Casey, we're on you
in 60 seconds.

01:27.887 --> 01:28.877
Uh, excuse me.

01:28.955 --> 01:30.184
Dan's got his hand raised.

01:30.256 --> 01:32.088
Why are we quoting
high-level sources

01:32.158 --> 01:33.887
inside the Swiss
Olympic Committee

01:33.960 --> 01:35.928
on Helsinki's bid
for the 2010 Olympics?

01:35.995 --> 01:38.259
-- What's the problem?
-- Helsinki's in Finland.

01:39.332 --> 01:40.265
Really?

01:40.333 --> 01:41.801
Yeah.
Don't worry. I got it.

01:41.868 --> 01:42.858
Are you sure?

01:43.670 --> 01:45.263
Am I sure that Helsinki's
in Finland?

01:45.338 --> 01:46.533
Yeah. I'm quite sure.

01:46.606 --> 01:48.005
I thought it was in Sweden.

01:48.074 --> 01:49.974
It says "unnamed Swiss
Olympic officials."

01:50.043 --> 01:52.535
Graphics! Which is it,
Sweden or Switzerland?

01:52.612 --> 01:53.841
It's in Finland.

01:53.913 --> 01:56.314
-- Elliott, get something up on the Net!
-- What do you need?

01:56.382 --> 01:58.180
We think Helsinki might be
in Finland.

01:58.251 --> 02:00.083
Yeah, we think
there's a pretty good chance.

02:00.153 --> 02:01.587
Man:
Coming in live in 15.

02:01.654 --> 02:03.349
<i>We'll change it
on the teleprompter.</i>

02:03.423 --> 02:05.187
Cool. We can go out
after the show.

02:05.258 --> 02:07.727
You can stay at my place. VVhatever
you need. VVhatever you need.

02:07.794 --> 02:09.853
I'm getting a divorce.
I don't need a cruise director.

02:09.929 --> 02:10.862
Right.

02:10.930 --> 02:12.523
My foul.

02:12.599 --> 02:14.158
Forget I said anything.

02:14.234 --> 02:16.601
<i>In 5...4...</i>

02:16.669 --> 02:20.435
<i>3...2...1.</i>

02:20.507 --> 02:21.497
Good evening, everybody.

02:21.574 --> 02:24.305
From New York City, I'm Dan
Rydell alongside Casey McCall.

02:24.377 --> 02:27.642
Those stories and more, plus we'll take
you live to the locker room at Arrowhead.

02:27.714 --> 02:29.307
All that coming up after this.

02:29.382 --> 02:32.317
You're watching "Sports Night"
on CSC, so stick around.

02:32.385 --> 02:34.319
<i>We're out. Up in 60.</i>

02:34.387 --> 02:36.151
Yeah. Finland.

02:36.222 --> 02:38.884
The national bird is
the whooping swan.

02:39.859 --> 02:41.520
-- Thank you.
-- Thank you.

02:45.165 --> 02:48.430
<i>Dan: Columbia, 34, Colgate, 3.
Who owes me money?</i>

02:49.502 --> 02:51.971
Thank you.

02:52.038 --> 02:52.971
Oh!

02:53.039 --> 02:54.700
Hey, Jason Grisham
got arrested

02:54.774 --> 02:56.708
in a strip bar
in Houston last night.

02:56.776 --> 02:58.972
[Chuckles ] That was
only a matter of time.

02:59.045 --> 03:00.479
Kim and Elliott are on it.

03:00.547 --> 03:03.482
Kim, Elliott.
Jason Grisham -- what's up?

03:03.550 --> 03:05.314
He shot 12-for-15
from the field,

03:05.385 --> 03:07.114
and then he went
to the Silver Key.

03:07.187 --> 03:09.747
-- It's a nude nightclub.
-- Topless only.

03:09.822 --> 03:13.224
A guy called him something he didn't like,
and Grisham hit him with a bottle of cognac.

03:13.293 --> 03:14.351
-- <i>It was brandy.</i>
-- <i>It was cognac.</i>

03:14.427 --> 03:15.417
<i>It was Courvoisier.</i>

03:15.495 --> 03:17.463
Courvoisier <i>is</i> cognac.

03:17.530 --> 03:20.693
You get me the lawyer, you get me the agent,
then get us Jason Grisham on the phone.

03:20.767 --> 03:22.565
-- We can't get Grisham on the phone.
-- Yes, you can.

03:22.635 --> 03:24.797
-- We are trying.
-- Try harder.

03:24.871 --> 03:26.464
32 points.
It was a career high.

03:26.539 --> 03:28.940
Then he sends a guy to
the hospital with 14 stitches.

03:29.008 --> 03:31.534
-- Can you imagine if he'd had
a lousy game? -- [Chuckles]

03:31.611 --> 03:32.578
You come in early?

03:32.645 --> 03:33.942
I came in early.

03:34.013 --> 03:35.708
You slept in the office?

03:35.782 --> 03:37.841
-- I came in early.
-- You came in yesterday.

03:37.917 --> 03:39.146
Mom...

03:39.219 --> 03:40.914
Have I told you about
my New York renaissance?

03:40.987 --> 03:43.388
Yeah. A lot. You've told me about
your New York renaissance a lot.

03:43.456 --> 03:45.220
<i>Last night's show.
What's up?</i>

03:45.291 --> 03:47.419
Grisham's free on bail,
Casey slept in his office,

03:47.493 --> 03:49.962
and I'm having
a New York renaissance.

03:50.029 --> 03:53.090
[Chuckles] Cool. Rundown
meeting's in five minutes.

03:53.166 --> 03:55.498
I think the show's going to hell
in a handbasket,

03:55.568 --> 03:57.559
and I'm ready to fire
the whole bunch of you.

03:57.637 --> 03:59.765
Yes, but you won't
'cause we're all family here,

03:59.839 --> 04:01.500
and I'm just like
a daughter to you.

04:01.574 --> 04:03.770
No, this is
a television show here,

04:03.843 --> 04:05.902
and you're very much like
an employee to me.

04:05.979 --> 04:08.243
I got to give Casey
some slack, Isaac.

04:08.314 --> 04:11.011
-- Why? -- Why do I have
to give him some slack?

04:11.084 --> 04:13.849
That's the question. If you can't
tell me, I can't tell the network.

04:13.920 --> 04:17.322
-- Isaac... -- What, is there something
going on between the two of you?

04:17.390 --> 04:19.051
-- Absolutely not.
-- Then why?

04:19.125 --> 04:21.321
Because I owe it to him,
that's why. We all do.

04:21.394 --> 04:22.862
Now he's having
some personal problems --

04:22.929 --> 04:25.421
Oh, I know all about
his problems.

04:25.498 --> 04:27.262
You know, the network
knows about his problems, too,

04:27.333 --> 04:29.301
as a result of which,
they become <i>my</i> problems.

04:29.369 --> 04:32.999
And I'm saying that at the very most,
I want them to be your problems.

04:33.072 --> 04:34.471
-- Got it.
-- Do you?

04:34.540 --> 04:35.530
-- Yes.
-- Good.

04:37.010 --> 04:40.275
It's a genuine renaissance,
Casey.

04:40.346 --> 04:42.110
I have lived in New York
my whole life.

04:42.181 --> 04:44.445
This is the time I should
be sick of it, but I'm not.

04:44.517 --> 04:46.849
-- 'Cause you're having a renaissance.
-- That's right.

04:46.919 --> 04:47.852
-- Really?
-- Yeah.

04:47.920 --> 04:50.287
Nobody cares.

04:50.356 --> 04:53.485
So how do we avoid these
Helsinki mishaps in the future?

04:53.559 --> 04:56.358
-- We've been short-handed since Phil and
Michael left. -- VVell, hire somebody.

04:56.429 --> 04:59.364
Natalie's been interviewing people
for an associate producer position,

04:59.432 --> 05:01.230
and I'm meeting her finalists
this afternoon.

05:01.301 --> 05:04.396
You guys, he is so
totally cute and intense

05:04.470 --> 05:05.960
with a dark mystery
about him that says,

05:06.039 --> 05:08.872
"This is not a technician,
this is an artist."

05:11.110 --> 05:14.444
VVell, before you hire him, can you
make sure he can find Finland on a map?

05:14.514 --> 05:17.313
You know what, Isaac?
Maybe let that go.

05:17.383 --> 05:20.353
You have Metropolitan Opera under
the baton of Mr. James Levine.

05:20.420 --> 05:22.684
-- <i>What is he talking about?</i>
-- <i>His New York renaissance.</i>

05:22.755 --> 05:24.018
-- Want to hear about it?
-- No.

05:24.090 --> 05:25.990
Good.
Quickly, now -- talk to me.

05:26.059 --> 05:28.391
7 through 17.
We got the whiparound with what?

05:28.461 --> 05:30.395
<i>Lambeau, 3Com, and Foxboro.</i>

05:30.463 --> 05:33.524
Casey's got Tampa Bay and the
mighty Bengals of Cincinnati.

05:33.599 --> 05:36.398
-- What's in Cincinnati? -- I/VeH,
the mighty Bengals, for one thing.

05:36.469 --> 05:38.233
-- <i>They're</i> gonna <i>cut Santori.</i>
-- <i>The placekicker?</i>

05:38.304 --> 05:40.500
He's made eight field-goal
attempts in three games

05:40.573 --> 05:42.405
and has connected on a grand
total of none of them.

05:42.475 --> 05:44.603
-- Oh, I've met him. He's a good guy.
-- Can't kick.

05:44.677 --> 05:46.111
-- He is a good guy.
-- Can't kick.

05:46.179 --> 05:48.671
-- He'll get picked up by another team.
-- No, he won't. You know why?

05:48.748 --> 05:51.149
-- Why?
-- <i>'Cause he can't kick.</i>

05:51.217 --> 05:54.187
All right, commercial one,
then on to The Dugout Report --

05:54.253 --> 05:55.550
I saw him kick in practice.

05:55.621 --> 05:59.057
At this level, they pretty much want
you to be able to kick in a game.

05:59.125 --> 06:00.490
Moving on,
from center ice --

06:00.560 --> 06:02.460
<i>I once kicked a 12-yard
field goal in a gym class.</i>

06:02.528 --> 06:06.294
VVell, then you should get yourself a tryout
for the mighty Bengals of Cincinnati.

06:06.366 --> 06:10.098
Excuse me. If anyone needs me, I'll
be hurling myself out the window.

06:10.169 --> 06:12.103
Plaza hotel, Oak Bar,
dry martini.

06:12.171 --> 06:14.105
New York at night, my friend.
This city never sleeps.

06:14.173 --> 06:17.837
<i>Commercial 2,
then on to segment 24.</i>

06:17.910 --> 06:20.402
Actually, I'd like to go back
to 23 if nobody minds.

06:20.480 --> 06:22.073
Any chance we could do it
a little later?

06:22.148 --> 06:24.742
-- I <i>want to move this along.</i> -- <i>The
network would like me to address this now.</i>

06:24.817 --> 06:27.718
J.J., Dana's the producer. We like to
give her the impression she's in charge.

06:27.787 --> 06:28.879
[Chuckling]

06:28.955 --> 06:30.480
It's just that we're
a little short on time.

06:30.556 --> 06:33.218
-- Segment 24 -- -- I have some
concerns about segment 23.

06:33.292 --> 06:35.556
Is this you or the network?

06:35.628 --> 06:38.256
In these meetings, Casey, mine
is the voice of the network.

06:38.331 --> 06:39.560
Wow, J.J.!

06:39.632 --> 06:41.760
What are your concerns?

06:41.834 --> 06:42.960
Who is Ntozake Nelson,

06:43.035 --> 06:45.629
and why are you doing a
3-minute-and-20-second feature on him?

06:45.705 --> 06:46.467
Natalie!

06:46.539 --> 06:50.271
Ntozake Nelson's a South African
distance runner -- 15,000 meters.

06:50.343 --> 06:53.438
As a schoolteacher in Jamestown, he led
protests against the white majority.

06:53.513 --> 06:54.947
That's swell,
but, folks, I have --

06:55.014 --> 06:56.072
-- No, I --
-- Hey!

06:57.483 --> 06:59.417
He was beaten up
and thrown in jail.

06:59.485 --> 07:02.750
His legs were broken, and the doctor
said he'd never walk without a cane.

07:02.822 --> 07:05.792
He's 41 years old, and guess
what he's doing tonight.

07:05.858 --> 07:07.792
It doesn't matter, 'cause I've
already changed the channel.

07:07.860 --> 07:09.521
He's running
in the World Pacific Games,

07:09.595 --> 07:12.895
an event this network is
carrying live tonight at 9:00.

07:12.965 --> 07:15.195
The Ntozake Nelson feature
is promoting --

07:15.268 --> 07:17.703
Look, I am all for you guys
spotlighting our other programming.

07:17.770 --> 07:21.400
But can't we find a good-looking 22-year-old
American who might actually win?

07:21.474 --> 07:24.603
VVell, if you find him, send him over
to my place, but in the meantime --

07:24.677 --> 07:27.647
Lo0k,lhave a ratings book on my
desk that's very instructive.

07:27.713 --> 07:30.614
Now, it says that our key demographics,
including 11- to 17-year-olds

07:30.683 --> 07:33.812
who watch your morning rerun over
breakfast, do not want to see features

07:33.886 --> 07:37.288
<i>about 41-year-old, politically oppressed
Third World distance runners.</i>

07:37.356 --> 07:39.757
Now, they are instructing us, and I
think it's a good idea to listen.

07:39.826 --> 07:41.920
I've got Jason Grisham
on the phone.

07:41.994 --> 07:44.361
<i>J.J., Danny and I have
hosted shows</i>

07:44.430 --> 07:46.558
in the fifth- and third-largest
markets in the country,

07:46.632 --> 07:49.067
and we've received awards
for journalistic excellence.

07:49.135 --> 07:51.729
I'd prefer not to take my
instructions from 11-year-olds.

07:51.804 --> 07:53.602
And the next time you sit
in our rundown meeting

07:53.673 --> 07:55.607
and I hear the voice of the
network come out of your mouth,

07:55.675 --> 07:57.404
I'm gonna put my foot
on your throat.

08:00.813 --> 08:03.373
[Door opens, closes]

08:03.449 --> 08:05.213
You ever ride
the subway all day long,

08:05.284 --> 08:06.945
I mean,
just for the fun of it?

08:09.689 --> 08:12.283
Natalie, Kim, Elliott,
everybody else,

08:12.358 --> 08:14.349
um, you want to step outside
as well, please?

08:15.761 --> 08:17.251
Go ahead.

08:18.331 --> 08:20.299
[Dana clears throat]

08:23.102 --> 08:25.537
I'd like to apologize for Casey's
performance in these meetings lately.

08:25.605 --> 08:28.836
<i>Dana, I'm not concerned with Casey's
performance in these meetings lately.</i>

08:28.908 --> 08:30.637
Well, I appreciate
your understanding.

08:30.710 --> 08:33.611
I'm concerned with Casey's
performance on the air lately.

08:33.679 --> 08:35.203
-- What's your point?
-- My point is...

08:35.280 --> 08:38.876
at the moment, Casey has
less on-air charm and charisma

08:38.951 --> 08:41.818
than my high school driving
instructor, and you know it, Dan.

08:41.888 --> 08:43.686
<i>Now, I think
the time has come</i>

08:43.756 --> 08:46.487
for you to think about the
possibility of another partner.

08:46.559 --> 08:48.960
I'm not gonna do the show with your
high school driving instructor, J.J.,

08:49.028 --> 08:50.518
if that's what you're
asking me, okay, so...

08:51.898 --> 08:53.662
Who will you do
the show with?

08:53.733 --> 08:55.064
I'll do the show with Casey.

08:55.134 --> 08:57.967
You've got a very big future
at this network, Dan --

08:58.037 --> 09:02.133
My future is writing and anchoring a sports
program with my partner, Casey McCall.

09:02.208 --> 09:05.803
Now, if it's here, it's here. If
it's not, it is someplace else.

09:05.878 --> 09:09.212
For right now I'm gonna forget
this conversation ever took place.

09:10.249 --> 09:11.546
Dana, Isaac,
you guys need me?

09:11.617 --> 09:13.312
No. Thanks, Dan.
You're done.

09:14.520 --> 09:16.079
I really got to admire

09:16.155 --> 09:19.614
the way you manhandled
my staff this morning, J.J.

09:19.692 --> 09:21.126
Look, Isaac,
I have a specific --

09:21.193 --> 09:22.126
Look...

09:22.194 --> 09:24.094
don't take me on.

09:27.300 --> 09:29.962
The network's not gonna
wait forever.

09:32.972 --> 09:34.906
[Door opens, closes]

09:34.974 --> 09:36.499
It's your call, Dana.

09:36.576 --> 09:39.238
But pretty soon,
it's gonna be my call.

09:39.312 --> 09:41.440
'Cause here's the thing --

09:41.514 --> 09:43.915
I can't let it be
their call.

09:48.287 --> 09:49.618
Yeah.

09:53.826 --> 09:56.158
They can put a Tonka truck
on Mars and send me pictures,

09:56.228 --> 09:59.095
but I can't get a decent satellite
signal from Buenos Aires.

09:59.165 --> 10:00.257
Excuse me. Ma'am?

10:00.333 --> 10:02.529
That's probably because of
a high-pressure system

10:02.602 --> 10:05.299
building up around 32 degrees
south latitude.

10:05.371 --> 10:06.930
It'll blow by in two hours.

10:07.006 --> 10:09.168
-- There's weather in outer space?
-- Uh, no, maflam.

10:09.241 --> 10:12.541
But I think you're leasing time on
the East Tech keyhole satellite,

10:12.612 --> 10:16.105
and their signal gets cleared through
a tracking station in Mexico City.

10:16.182 --> 10:18.116
Yeah, but the point
I'm making is that I can't --

10:18.184 --> 10:19.345
Who -- Who --
Who is this?

10:20.019 --> 10:21.544
I'm Jeremy Goodwin.

10:21.621 --> 10:24.022
Oh, you're here for
the associate producer job.

10:24.090 --> 10:26.752
Yes, and let me just say that it is an
extraordinary honor to even be asked --

10:26.826 --> 10:29.056
-- I'm not ready for you yet.
-- I'll sit right here.

10:29.128 --> 10:30.425
32 degrees latitude.

10:30.496 --> 10:32.590
-- South latitude.
-- Ah. I get them mixed up.

10:32.665 --> 10:34.155
Common mistake.

10:36.435 --> 10:38.369
-- Hey.
-- Casey.

10:38.437 --> 10:42.101
Listen, I need you to take 30
seconds off the NFL injury report

10:42.174 --> 10:44.336
and give it to me for the, uh, intro
on ACC recruiting violations.

10:44.410 --> 10:45.377
-- Fine.
-- Thanks.

10:45.444 --> 10:47.037
You're screwing up
my show, Casey.

10:48.047 --> 10:49.310
Keep the 30 seconds.

10:49.382 --> 10:51.282
-- That's not what I mean.
-- I know. I was joking.

10:51.350 --> 10:54.376
-- I know you were joking. -- Yeah, I could tell
by the way you didn't laugh at all when I said it.

10:54.453 --> 10:57.821
That's 'cause I'm mad at you and also,
it wasn't that funny. [Chuckles]

10:57.890 --> 11:01.258
Dana, did you come in here
to give me a pep talk?

11:01.327 --> 11:02.852
'Cause if you came in here
to give me a pep talk,

11:02.928 --> 11:05.989
can we assume that it already happened,
that it worked, and that I'm peppy?

11:06.065 --> 11:07.658
Casey, sit down.

11:07.733 --> 11:10.862
Now, I know you think that there are
250 other people in this business

11:10.936 --> 11:12.700
-- No, I don't think there are 250 other people who can
produce this show. -- who could produce this show.

11:12.772 --> 11:14.604
Yes, you do, and whether you're
right or whether you're wrong,

11:14.674 --> 11:17.234
I'm the one that has the job,
and I love it.

11:17.309 --> 11:19.368
